<p>
<figure><img src="/images/palimpsests/2020/image03.jpg"
         alt="Exercise"/>
</figure>
</p>
<p>
The other day, I was reminded of my high school math teacher and how combinatorics was one of the few topics that interested me. The ability to envision an universe of possibilities within a given scenario was delightful. This morning, I combined that memory with an idea that has been occupying my mind lately—writing as an exercise of reflection and discovery. The lessons never end…</p>
<div id="outline-container-headline-1" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="headline-1">
Combinatorial analysis exercise I
</h2>
<div id="outline-text-headline-1" class="outline-text-2">
<p>
I write to discover what I think.<br>
I think to write what I discover.<br>
I discover to think what I write.<br>
I write to think what I discover.<br>
I think to discover what I write.<br>
I discover to write what I think.</p>
</div>
</div>
]]></content:encoded></item><item><title>Party of the bothered ones</title><link>https://eternodevir.com/palimpsests/party-of-the-bothered-ones/</link><pubDate>Wed, 12 Feb 2020 00:57:28 -0300</pubDate><author>Vinícius Moraes</author><guid>https://eternodevir.com/palimpsests/party-of-the-bothered-ones/</guid><description>A bothered person talks about their bother. Some bothered people agree, other bothered people disagree. At the party, the unbothered people are divided into two groups of bothered people: those who are not bothered by the annoyance itself, but by the fact that there are so many bothered people bothering; and those who are not bothered by anything at all, except for the unbothered being bothered by so many bothered people, which is known to cause them deep annoyance.</description><content:encoded>&lt;p>
A bothered person talks about their bother. Some bothered people agree, other bothered people disagree. At the party, the unbothered people are divided into two groups of bothered people: those who are not bothered by the annoyance itself, but by the fact that there are so many bothered people bothering; and those who are not bothered by anything at all, except for the unbothered being bothered by so many bothered people, which is known to cause them deep annoyance.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>
In the end, the only ones truly not bothered were those who decided not to go to the party—which, certainly, bothered a lot of people. That is, it seemed that way… at least until they realized they had not even been invited.&lt;/p></content:encoded></item><item><title>For Street Cinema memories</title><link>https://eternodevir.com/palimpsests/for-street-cinema-memories/</link><pubDate>Sun, 03 Feb 2019 20:36:05 -0300</pubDate><author>Vinícius Moraes</author><guid>https://eternodevir.com/palimpsests/for-street-cinema-memories/</guid><description>I do remain with my positions of a third-worldist cinema. An independent cinema from an economic and artistic point of view, which does not let aesthetic creativity disappear in the name of commercial objectivity and political immediacy.
— Glauber Rocha, director
Cinearte Palace, Juiz de Fora, 2017
Glauber Rocha taught me that Cinema Novo had the potential to be a national cinema that was not purely commercial. A place for art, experimentation, transformation, and freedom.</description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<blockquote>
<p>I do remain with my positions of a third-worldist cinema. An independent cinema from an economic and artistic point of view, which does not let aesthetic creativity disappear in the name of commercial objectivity and political immediacy.</p>
<p>
— Glauber Rocha, director</p>
</blockquote>
<p>
<figure><img src="/images/palimpsests/2019/image00.jpg"
         alt="Cinearte Palace"/><figcaption>
            <p>Cinearte Palace, Juiz de Fora, 2017</p>
        </figcaption>
</figure>
</p>
<p>
Glauber Rocha taught me that Cinema Novo had the potential to be a national cinema that was not purely commercial. A place for art, experimentation, transformation, and freedom. Each director with their own unique vision, creating a space of resistance to the predetermined and obvious formulas of Hollywood.</p>
<p>
However, it became increasingly difficult to find similar expressions of will, especially with the growing dominance of major US productions in Brazil. The cinema experience was transformed, shifting to large shopping centers, and popular festivals and local productions were put in the background by blockbusters. Despite this, some places for encountering the unknown still resist.</p>
<p>
<figure><img src="/images/palimpsests/2019/image01.jpg"
         alt="Cine Roxy"/><figcaption>
            <p>Cine Roxy, Rio de Janeiro, 2018</p>
        </figcaption>
</figure>
</p>
<p>
In my search for one of these places in Passau, a small town on the border of Germany and Austria, I was fortunate to find a street cinema showing the Brazilian film <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GxCOCthjc7o">Corpo Elétrico</a>—which I watched during one of the only two sessions that took place in Juiz de Fora. The feature, by Marcelo Caetano, reminds me of Glauber&#39;s genuine will to create something instigating that, more than understanding, dares to invite us to feel. In the darkness of the emptied rows of that German street cinema, I reaffirmed how surprising and fascinating these spaces are that still encourage diversity and experimentation. After having lived near the last street cinema in Juiz de Fora for seven years, I have never felt so close to home even when so far away.</p>
